Voice and Sight Results

Colin Leslie

3/12/2020

source('scripts/vp_data.R')

Introduction

This report details results from the 2016 and 2018 rounds of the Voice and Sight Monitoring Program (2014 available as a separate report).

Monitoring Background

The 2014 - 2018 Voice and Sight Monitoring Program consisted of several different monitoring measures associated with dog management on OSMP lands. These include:

  • Interactions on Voice and Sight designated trails
  • Complinace with carrying a leash on-person for Voice and Sight trails a
  • Compliance on Leash Required trails
  • Compliance on Seasonal Leash Required trails
  • On/Off leash ratios on Voice and Sight designated trails b

a only conducted in 2014

b only conducted in 2018

All of the measures were designed to evaluate specific sets of dog management criteria using naturalistic1 observation methods that would capture day-to-day, on-the-ground conditions associated with dog management on OSMP lands. The goal of this monitoring effort was to assess conditions at a system-wide scale by conducting randomized field observations that were both spatially and temporally distributed. Constructing a large sample frame of locations, distributed across the majority of the OSMP land system, minimized the probability that conditions at any one location would exhert undue leverage the final results. Again, the goal was to evaluate dog management across the land system as a whole, not to evaluate or “target” any specific locations.

Before we dive into the results, it is worth taking a moment to understand the relationship between the sample selection and analysis process. While the sample selection procedures required staff to select from a randomized combination of locations and times, the actual unit of analysis for all components is the visitor party2. Staff conducted observations at predefined locations were they could view a visitor party as they passed by a specific point or traversed a predefined section of trail. Staff utilized structured coding guides to systematically and objectively record attributes and behaviors of the visitor party under observation.

The specific number of visitor parties that were observed during each three hour period was variable, subject to both the general visitation levels of the location selected as well as random environmental variables, such as weather. It is for this reason that all observations have been aggregated within each observation type. It is neither possible nor appropriate to try and make stastical inferences regarding site specific compliance with dog management regulations.

Compositional Analysis

Session Distribution

Trained staff conducted direct observation in the field using a randomized sample of locations, dates and times. All collection types and sessions were conducted in three hour blocks. While individual start hours were randomized, we can classify each session broadly into AM, Mid-day, and PM sessions to get a sense of when collections took place across the day. This is significant as we know from both previous research and anectdotal observations that aspects of both human and dog visitation varty throughout the day. Simple randomization of observations times helped to minimize bias of overall results toward any particular type of temporally based visitation pattern.

sessions_official <- sessions_merge %>%
  mutate(Type = paste(regulation_class, monitoring_type, sep = " - "),
         start = as.POSIXct(format(timeStart, format = "%H:%M"), format = "%H:%M"),
         end = as.POSIXct(format(timeEnd, format = "%H:%M"), format = "%H:%M"),
         year = year(sessionDate),
         month = month(sessionDate),
         CommonDate = as.Date(paste0("2000-", format(sessionDate, "%j")), "%Y-%j"))

sessions_official %>%

  filter(No_Observations == 0) %>%
  group_by(Type, Year, All_Dogs) %>%
  summarise(count_of_groups = n()) %>%
  mutate(total_groups = sum(count_of_groups),
         proportion = count_of_groups / total_groups) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(percent = percent(proportion, 1)) %>%
  select(-proportion, -count_of_groups, `Sample Size` = total_groups) %>%
  spread(key = All_Dogs, value = percent, fill = 0) %>%
  kable("html", escape = F,
        caption = "Percent of visitor groups observed with") %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F, position = "left") %>%
  collapse_rows(columns = 1, valign = "top") %>%
  add_header_above(c(" " = 3, "Dogs in visitor party" = 5)) %>%
  column_spec(4:7, width = "2cm")

Compliance Analysis

Leash and Tag Status

Tag display for all dogs observed in 2018 by trail regulation type, leash and tag status.

source('scripts/vp_data.R')

vp_data %>%
  filter(No_Observations == 0) %>%
  filter(Year == 2018, Type != "Voice and Sight - Behavioral") %>%
  select(Type, Leash_Tag, Leash_No_Tag = Leash_NoTag, Leash_Unsure, Off_Tag, Off_No_Tag = Off_NoTag, Off_Unsure) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(2:7), names_to = "Status", values_to = "Count") %>%
  group_by(Type, Status) %>%
  summarise(Count = sum(Count)) %>%
  mutate(Frequency = Count/sum(Count),
         Leash = c(rep("On Leash", 3), rep("Off Leash", 3)),
         Status = gsub("_", " ", Status),
         Tag = substr(Status, if_else(grepl("Leash", Status), 7, 5), nchar(Status))) %>%
  select(-Count, -Status) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(Frequency = percent(Frequency, 1)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Type, values_from = Frequency) %>%
  kable("html", escape = F,
        caption = "",
        col.names = c("Status", "Tag", "Permanent", "Seasonal", "Voice and Sight")) %>%
  collapse_rows(columns = 1, valign = "top") %>%
  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F, position = "left")
